NMR  spectra  were  recorded  on  a  Bruker  Avance  III  with  cryo  probe  at  resonance  frequencies  of  600 MHz  and  150 MHz  for  1H  and  13C  measurements,  respectively.  Dimethylmalonyl-CoA  (dmM-CoA)  was  synthesized  as  described  below,  malonyl-  (M-CoA)  and  methylmalonyl- CoA  (mM-CoA)  were  purchased  from  Sigma-Aldrich  (96%  purity),  and  buffer  components  were purchased from Roth.  Targeted Gene Inactivation in S. tendae HKI 0179  In  order  to  inactivate  cerJ  by  PCR  targeting,1  primer  pairs  KOACPsynUP  (5’-GGA  CGT  CAC CCC ACC CCC GAA CCG GGA GAG GTC TCC ATG ATT CCG GGG ATC CGT  CGA  CC-3’)  and  KOACPsynDP  (5’-GGC  GGC  CGC  TGA  CCC  ACG  GCC  CGC  CGG

CGC  CCC  CGT  TCA  TGT  AGG  CTG  GAG  CTG  CTT  C-3’)  were  designed  for  amplification  of  the  apramycin  resistance  cassette  from  pIJ773.  A  1.4 kb  PCR  product  was  generated and introduced into  E. coli BW25113 carrying recombination plasmid pIJ790 and  cosmid  2D5  (harboring  the  cervimycin  gene  cluster  upstream  of  cerD).  The  resulting  recombinant  plasmid,  pMP49,  was  introduced  into  S. tendae HKI  179  (wild  type)  by  conjugation.  Exconjugants  with  cerJ  replaced  by  a  apramycin  resistance  cassette  were  confirmed  by  PCR  using  primer  pairs  KompCerJfw  (5’-GAA  CCG  GGA  GAG  GTC  TCC  ATG-3’)  and  KompCerJrv  (5’-CGC  CGG  CGC  CCC  CGT  TCA-3’).  Further  production,  analysis and purification of the cervimycins produced by S. tendae ∆cerJ::apr was performed  as described previously using apramycin as selection marker.2  Quality Control and Final Purification of Recombinant CerJ  The  purity  of  the  enzyme  was  checked  on  a  10%  SDS-PAGE  gel  and  by  MALDI  (ultrafleXtremeTM,  Bruker)  measurement  (see  Supplementary  Figure  3c).  The  CerJ-His  monomer was obtained  at  m/z = 37525 (calcd. 37527,  ∆ = 75 ppm) and  the dimer  at  m/z  =  75085 (calcd. 75054, ∆ = 415 ppm)  Before  crystallization,  a  size-exclusion  chromatography  (SEC)  using  a  Superdex  S75/16/60

column  and  SEC-buffer  (15  mM  HEPES  pH  7.5,  150  mM  NaCl)  was  performed  to  yield  a  pure  protein  solution.  Folding  of  CerJ  was  proven  by  CD-spectroscopy  and  DLS  (dynamic  light  scattering),  revealing  a  monomodal  protein  solution.  Finally,  the  protein  was  concentrated to 13 mg mL-1, flash-frozen and stored at –80 °C until crystallization.  Crystallization, Structure Determination, Refinement and Substrate Modeling  CerJ was crystallized at  20 °C by hanging drop  vapor diffusion mixing the protein solution  (1.0 µL, 10 mg mL-1) with crystallization buffer (1.5 µL, Hampton Research, Crystal Screen  1, condition 22) on a siliconized cover slide which was placed over the reservoir solution (500  µL, 22.5% PEG 4000, 100 mM Tris/HCl pH 8.5, 200 mM sodium acetate). The crystals grew  within  6  days  to  a  final  size  of  250x250x200  µm3.  To  produce  heavy-atom  derivatized  crystals  of  CerJ,  the  crystals  were  transferred  stepwise  into  the  crystallization  buffer  containing  30  mM  uranyl  nitrate  and  incubated  for  3  days  at  20  °C.  For  data  collection  the  crystals were mounted onto a loop and flash-frozen in liquid nitrogen until data collection was  performed.  Incorporation  of  CoA  was  achieved  by  transferring  a  CerJ  crystal  into  a  freshly  prepared  mother  liquor  containing  5  mM  methylmalonyl  coenzyme  A  (mM-CoA).  After  incubation for 16 h the crystal was flash-frozen in liquid nitrogen. Crystals of malonyl-CerJ  were prepared with the same procedure but 8 mM malonyl coenzyme A (M-CoA) were used

and  the  crystal  was  left  in  the  soaking  solution  for  24  h.  To  incorporate  cervimycin  K  (CerviK) we dissolved purified cervimycin K in methanol and prepared a saturated solution of  cervimycin  K  in  the  crystallization  condition  (approximately  4  mM).  The  CerJ  crystal  was  transferred in four steps into the cervimycin K solution and was left in the solution for 6 days  at  20  °C.  Every  second  day  the  crystal  was  transferred  into  a  freshly  prepared  soaking  For phase determination two datasets of the uranyl containing CerJ crystal were collected at a  wavelength  of  1.7  Å  and  0.95  Å.  A  freshly  prepared  crystal  of  CerJ  was  used  to  collect  a  native dataset at a wavelength of 1.0 Å. All datasets were indexed, integrated and scaled using  XDS  and  XSCALE.3  Initially,  three  major  uranium  sites  were  identified  using  the  SAD  protocol  implemented  in  SHELXD.4  These  heavy  atom  positions  were  utilized  for  substructure  refinement,  phasing  and  density  modification  as  implemented  in  autoSHARP.5  The resulting experimental electron density map was of good quality (figure of merit 0.411)  and  allowed  manual  chain  tracing  which  resulted  in  a  crude  partial  model.  This  model  was  then  transferred  to  the  native  dataset  using  rigid  body  refinement  implemented  in  REFMAC5.6 Several cycles of manual building with COOT7 and refinement with REFMAC5  completed the model. Water molecules were placed using ARP/wARP solvent8 and checked  manually with COOT. For the final refinement steps each protomer was assigned to one TLS9

group  per  protomer  yielding  a  model  of  excellent  quality  (Supplementary  Table  2).  All  structures  were  validated  using  WHATCHECK10  and  SFCHECK10  (Supplementary  Table 2). Figures were generated using POVscript+11 and POVRAY (www.povray.org).   Phasing of the substrate structures was performed by rigid body refinement using REFMAC5.  To avoid model bias the atoms were shaken in silico by simulated annealing implemented in  PHENIX.12  The  models  were  then  refined  in  several  cycles.  The  late  steps  of  refinement  involved the inspection of the substrate omit maps, which were used to model the substrates.  For this propose either the REFMAC5 library was used or the ligand including a library was  prepared using PRODRG.13 Although we had significant electron density along the substrate  channel of subunit A in CerJ-CerviK, it was unexpected as the substrate channel of subunit B  was completely free, whereas subunit A was partially constricted by crystal packing contacts  of a symmetry related protomer. We tried to insert the tail portion of cervimycin K into that  density but temperature factors stayed high for modeling a single cervimycin K conformation  (65.3  Å2).  We  then  tried  to  model  polyethylene  glycol  from  crystallization  buffer  into  that  density,  but  too  much  positive  electron  density  remained.  Moreover,  the  identical  soaking  procedure as for CerJ-CerviK was applied to another CerJ crystal using identical solutions but  lacking cervimycin K content. This was done to verify a relationship between cervimycin K  soaking and the resulting electron density. Here, we did not observe any density in the active  center  of  both  subunits  (data  not  shown).  This  clearly  indicates  that  the  obtained  electron  density results from cervimycin K soaking protocol and is related to the incorporation of the  substrate.  Since  a  part  of  the  cervimycin  K  would  not  fulfill  all  criteria  of  a  valid  substrate

structure,  we  decided  to  leave  the  electron  density  unfilled  for  PDB  submission.  A  crude  model adjusted by the (Fo-Fc)-omit map is shown in  Figure 5c (see main text), which is in  good agreement with the other data observed for the catalysis.  QuickChange II XL Site-Directed Mutagenesis Kit (Stratagene) was applied to generate site- specific  mutations  on  CerJ.  To  confirm  the  active  site,  following  mutant  primer  pairs  were  designed to generate the appropriate CerJ mutants: CerJ C116A_fw (5’-GCC TGG CCC AGC  GCG CCA ACG GCG  GGA TGG-3’) and CerJ C116A_rv (5’-CCA TCC CGC CGT TGG  CGC GCT GGG CCA  GGC-3’, codon encoding  Ala underlined); CerJ C116S_fw (5’-GCC  TGG CCC AGC GCA GCA ACG GCG GGA TGG-3’) and CerJ C116S_rv (5’- CCA TCC  CGC  CGT  TGC  TGC  GCT  GGG  CCA  GGC-3’,  codon  encoding  Ser  underlined);  CerJ  H295N_fw  (5’-  CAC  CAC  GGG  CAA  TGT  CGG  TGC  GGG  CGA  CCA  G  -3’)  and  CerJ  H295N_rv  (5’-  CTG  GTC  GCC  CGC  ACC  GAC  ATT  GCC  CGT  GGT  G  -3’,  codon  encoding Asn underlined); CerJ D300A_fw (5’- CAT GTC GGT GCG GGC GCC CAG TAC  GCG GGG CTC -3’) and CerJ D300A_rv (5’- GAG CCC CGC GTA CTG GGC GCC CGC  ACC  GAC  ATG  -3’,  codon  encoding  Ala  underlined).  For  all  mutations,  template  plasmid

pTB16 was used, and the successful mutagenesis was verified by sequencing. Finally, enzyme  production  and  purification  of  the  CerJ  mutants  was  carried  out  using  the  same  strategy  as  In  the  implemented  enzyme  assays  the  same  protein  concentration  of  the  soluble  protein  mutants  was  taken.  The  incubation  time  was  varied  between  1-15 h.  The  accordance  of  the  protein  structure  of  the  soluble  CerJ  mutants  was  verified  by  circular  dichroism  (J-815  CD  spectrometer, JASCO) (see Supplementary Figure 3d).  Enzyme  kinetic  studies  were  performed  for  M-CoA,  mM-CoA  and  dmM-CoA  varying  the  substrate  concentration  in  the  range  of  150-2,200 µM  in  the  presence  of  580  nM  CerJ.  Cervimycin K  was  supplied  in  excess  (2,500 µM)  directly  under  the  point  of  dissolubility.  The  reaction  was  stopped  after  10 min  and  the  aqueous  phase  was  analyzed  by  HPLC  (Shimadzu)  operating  with  a  C18  Synergi  4 µm  Hydro  RP  80 A  column  (Phenomenex).  A  gradient from 5-23% solvent B in 24 min (solvent A: 0.1% HCOOH in H2O, solvent B: 100%  CH3CN) at a flow rate of 1 mL min-1 and a UV detection wave length of 260 nm was used.  The peak areas were quantified and calculated into substrate concentrations.  To  obtain  a  regression  factor  of  higher  than  0.97,  we  fitted  a  sigmoidal  approach  (Hill  equation) (see Supplementary Figure 3e). The Hill factors range from 1.2 for M-CoA to 2.1

for mM- and dmM-CoA, which is suggestive for a positive cooperativity during the enzyme  HPLC-MS Monitoring of Biotransformation Assay  The  enzyme  reaction  was  monitored  by  HPLC  analysis  of  the  crude  extract  using  a  BDS  2.4 µm  Hypersil  C18  column  (100  ×  2.1 mm;  Thermo  Scientific)  and  a  gradient  of  50-98%  solvent B  in  15 min  (solvent  A:  0.1%  HCOOH  in  H2O,  solvent  B:  100%  MeOH)  at  a  flow  rate  of  0.15 mL min-1  monitored  at  250 nm.  This  chromatographic  unit  was  coupled  to  an  Exactive (Thermo Scientific) ESI mass spectrometer. Fragmentation of the cervimycins was  achieved with 50 eV collision energy and the resulted fragments were detected in the positive  Synthesis of Dimethylmalonyl-CoA (dmM-CoA)  dmM-CoA  was  synthesized  in  analogy  to  a  method  reported  by  Banerjee.14  Briefly,  dimethylmalonic acid (dmM, 1 mmol), dissolved in acetonitrile (10 mL), was esterified with  thiophenol  (TP,  0.98 mmol)  and  dimethylaminopyridine  (DMAP,  0.2 mmol)  by  dropwise  addition of coupling reagent 1-ethyl-3-(3-dimethylaminopropyl) carbodiimide (EDC, 1 mmol)  dissolved in acetonitrile (10 mL), at 0 °C within 1 h. After 3 h, the reaction was stopped by  addition of water (5 mL) and 1 N hydrochloric acid (1 mL). Product and residual educts were  extracted  with  diethylether  (3x  20  mL).  Dimethylmalonyl  thiophenyl  ester  acid  (dmM-TP)

was  purified  by  open  column  chromatography  on  silica  gel  (Serva).  Subsequently,  the  monoester  was  transesterified  with  coenzyme A  (CoA)  to  obtain  dmM-CoA.  dmM-TP  (27 µmol),  dissolved  in  acetonitrile  (40 µL),  was  incubated  with  CoA  (5.4 µmol)  in  sodium  bicarbonate buffer (600 µL, pH 9) at 10 °C, 600 rpm in a thermoblock (Eppendorf) for 120 h.  The  reaction  was  stopped  by  acidification  with  1 N  HCl  (0.1 mL).  Resultant  TP  was  recovered by extraction with diethylether (3 x 1 mL). The aqueous phase was extracted with  ethyl acetate (3 x 1 mL) to remove dmM, and then the aqueous phase was lyophilized.
